<h3>Typography in charts</h3>
<p>Text should help users quickly understand the data without competing with visual elements. Use NSW Government primary typeface, Public Sans. If this is not possible, use Arial as fallback.</p>

<h4>Minimum text sizes</h4>
<div class="nsw-grid">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-12 nsw-col-md-8 nsw-col-lg-8">
    <div class="nsw-section nsw-section--white nsw-block nsw-p-x-sm nsw-p-top-sm">
      <div class="nsw-table nsw-table--valign-middle nsw-docs__table-wrap">
        <table>
          <caption class="sr-only">Minimum text sizes for chart elements</caption>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Element</th>
              <th>Size</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Chart title</td>
              <td>16 to 18px</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Axis labels</td>
              <td>12 to 14px</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Dataset labels</td>
              <td>12 to 14px</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Data labels</td>
              <td>12px minimum</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Notes or sources</td>
              <td>11 to 12px</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<p>Avoid text smaller than 12px in digital charts.</p>

<h4>Text alignment</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Y-axis labels: right aligned</li>
  <li>X-axis labels: centred</li>
  <li>Dataset labels: placed close to the data they describe</li>
  <li>Direct labelling is preferred over legends where possible.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Number formatting</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Use commas for thousands (for example, <code>1,000</code>).</li>
  <li>Avoid spaces between digits, as screen readers may read them incorrectly.</li>
  <li>Use consistent decimal precision.</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="configure-tools-with-good-defaults">6. Configure tools with good defaults</h2>
<p>DDS does not prescribe tools. Tool defaults are not automatically compliant.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Apply the official NSW chart theme where available.</li>
  <li>Override default colour and typography settings.</li>
  <li>Test accessibility in the rendered environment.</li>
  <li>If a tool cannot meet requirements, provide an alternative.</li>
  <li>Consider accessibility capability when selecting vendors.</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="examples">Common chart pitfalls</h2>
<p>These examples show common issues and better implementations. Use them to spot risks early and improve consistency.</p>

<h3>Example 1: Truncated axis and unclear labels</h3>
<div class="nsw-grid nsw-m-top-sm">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--dont"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">cancel</span><span>Don't</span></div>
    <p>Column chart starts at 90, labels are rotated and the title does not explain the timeframe.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example1Bad" data-chart-height="320" role="img" aria-label="Column chart with truncated axis and rotated labels."></canvas>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Exaggerates differences by truncating the axis.</li>
      <li>Missing units and time period.</li>
      <li>Long labels are hard to read.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--do"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">check_circle</span><span>Do</span></div>
    <p>Use a horizontal bar chart that starts at zero with direct labels and a clear timeframe.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example1Good" data-chart-height="320" role="img" aria-label="Horizontal bar chart starting at zero with clear labels."></canvas>
    </div>
    <div class="nsw-table nsw-table--valign-middle nsw-docs__table-wrap nsw-m-top-sm">
      <table>
        <caption class="sr-only">Service completions by region (Jan to Jun 2025)</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Region</th>
            <th scope="col">Completions</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Illawarra Shoalhaven</th>
            <td>96</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Central Coast</th>
            <td>101</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Hunter New England</th>
            <td>98</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Western NSW</th>
            <td>104</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Set the chart canvas to a white background.</li>
      <li>Start the axis at zero or clearly indicate truncation.</li>
      <li>Include timeframe and unit in the title.</li>
      <li>Keep labels readable and aligned.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example 2: Colour-only differentiation</h3>
<div class="nsw-grid nsw-m-top-sm">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--dont"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">cancel</span><span>Don't</span></div>
    <p>Stacked bar uses red and green only, with no labels and low contrast.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example2Bad" data-chart-height="320" role="img" aria-label="Stacked bar chart using red and green only with no labels."></canvas>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Relies on colour alone to communicate meaning.</li>
      <li>Insufficient contrast for some users.</li>
      <li>No direct labels or markers.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--do"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">check_circle</span><span>Do</span></div>
    <p>Use accessible colours, clear contrast, and a supporting table for labels.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example2Good" data-chart-height="320" role="img" aria-label="Stacked bar chart with accessible colours and clear labels."></canvas>
    </div>
    <div class="nsw-table nsw-table--valign-middle nsw-docs__table-wrap nsw-m-top-sm">
      <table>
        <caption class="sr-only">Resolution by quarter</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Quarter</th>
            <th scope="col">Resolved on time</th>
            <th scope="col">Resolved late</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Q1</th>
            <td>120</td>
            <td>30</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Q2</th>
            <td>140</td>
            <td>25</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Q3</th>
            <td>110</td>
            <td>40</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Q4</th>
            <td>150</td>
            <td>20</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Set the chart canvas to a white background.</li>
      <li>Provide labels in a table, not colour alone.</li>
      <li>Meet WCAG contrast requirements.</li>
      <li>Keep the chart clear in greyscale and colour-blind testing.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example 3: Tooltip-only values</h3>
<div class="nsw-grid nsw-m-top-sm">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--dont"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">cancel</span><span>Don't</span></div>
    <p>Line chart shows values only on hover with no table or summary.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example3Bad" data-chart-height="280" role="img" aria-label="Line chart with values available only on hover."></canvas>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Keyboard and touch users cannot access key values.</li>
      <li>No text alternative for screen readers.</li>
      <li>Users cannot verify exact values.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--do"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">check_circle</span><span>Do</span></div>
    <p>Include a summary and a semantic table for the same data.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example3Good" data-chart-height="280" role="img" aria-label="Line chart with a summary and data table."></canvas>
    </div>
    <p class="nsw-m-top-sm"><strong>Summary:</strong> Applications rose steadily from January to May, with a small drop in June.</p>
    <div class="nsw-table nsw-table--valign-middle nsw-docs__table-wrap nsw-m-top-sm">
      <table>
        <caption class="sr-only">Online applications by month</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Month</th>
            <th scope="col">Applications</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">January</th>
            <td>220</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">February</th>
            <td>260</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">March</th>
            <td>310</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">April</th>
            <td>370</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">May</th>
            <td>420</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">June</th>
            <td>390</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Set the chart canvas to a white background.</li>
      <li>Use summary text for the key insight.</li>
      <li>Provide precise values in a table.</li>
      <li>Keep interactions keyboard accessible.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example 4: Too many pie segments</h3>
<div class="nsw-grid nsw-m-top-sm">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--dont"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">cancel</span><span>Don't</span></div>
    <p>Using many small slices makes comparison difficult and creates visual clutter.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example4Bad" data-chart-height="360" role="img" aria-label="Pie chart with twelve segments that are difficult to compare."></canvas>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Too many slices reduce readability.</li>
      <li>Small segments are hard to compare accurately.</li>
      <li>Large legends force users to cross-reference excessively.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-sm-6 nsw-docs__guideline">
    <div class="nsw-docs__guideline--do"><span class="material-icons nsw-material-icons" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true">check_circle</span><span>Do</span></div>
    <p>Keep pie segments limited so users can quickly compare relative share.</p>
    <div class="nsw-m-top-sm">
      <canvas id="example4Good" data-chart-height="360" role="img" aria-label="Pie chart with four clearly distinguishable segments and direct labels."></canvas>
    </div>
    <div class="nsw-table nsw-table--valign-middle nsw-docs__table-wrap nsw-m-top-sm">
      <table>
        <caption class="sr-only">Service channel share (Q2 2025)</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Channel</th>
            <th scope="col">Share</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Digital</th>
            <td>46%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Phone</th>
            <td>28%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">In person</th>
            <td>17%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Mail</th>
            <td>9%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Set the chart canvas to a white background.</li>
      <li>Limit pie segments to 2 to 4 where possible.</li>
      <li>Use labels and pattern support for clear distinction.</li>
      <li>Include direct labels, a clear title and percentages.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>


